00:55.522 --> 00:57.823
<i>Every living person
on this planet</i>

00:57.825 --> 01:02.061
<i>has their own unique
pair of eyes,</i>

01:02.063 --> 01:03.829
<i>each their own universe.</i>

01:17.544 --> 01:19.711
<i>My name is Dr. Ian Gray.</i>

01:21.082 --> 01:22.614
<i>I'm a father,</i>

01:22.616 --> 01:24.750
<i>a husband</i>

01:24.752 --> 01:27.152
<i>and I'm a scientist.</i>

01:33.827 --> 01:37.196
<i>When I was a child,
I realized that the camera</i>

01:37.198 --> 01:40.866
<i>was designed exactly like
the human eye,</i>

01:40.868 --> 01:42.234
<i>taking in light
through a lens,</i>

01:42.236 --> 01:45.471
<i>forming it into images.</i>

01:45.473 --> 01:47.739
<i>I began taking
as many pictures of eyes</i>

01:47.741 --> 01:49.541
<i>as I possibly could.</i>

02:09.863 --> 02:11.864
<i>I'd like to tell you the story</i>

02:11.866 --> 02:14.500
<i>of the eyes
that changed my world.</i>

02:14.502 --> 02:16.602
<i>Remember these eyes.</i>

02:16.604 --> 02:19.638
<i>Remember all the details
in these eyes.</i>

02:22.675 --> 02:24.409
<i>Okay.</i>

02:32.452 --> 02:35.854
<i>It started when I was
a 26-year-old PhD student</i>

02:35.856 --> 02:37.422
<i>living in New York.</i>

02:37.424 --> 02:40.626
<i>It was Halloween,
eight years ago.</i>

03:17.730 --> 03:19.698
You okay?

03:23.369 --> 03:25.304
I'm watching the moon.

03:34.447 --> 03:36.915
Can I take a picture
of your eyes?

03:36.917 --> 03:38.951
Why?

03:41.588 --> 03:43.555
It's just something I do.

03:47.894 --> 03:49.761
Okay.
Yeah?

03:49.763 --> 03:51.730
I've perfected this.

04:17.923 --> 04:19.658
Hi.

04:19.660 --> 04:20.940
Hi.

04:22.328 --> 04:25.530
Do you know the story
of the Phasianidae?

04:25.532 --> 04:27.266
The... No.

04:27.268 --> 04:28.567
What's that?

04:28.569 --> 04:30.402
It's a bird...

04:30.404 --> 04:33.905
that experiences all of time
in one instant.

04:33.907 --> 04:37.442
And she sings the song
of love and anger

04:37.444 --> 04:39.611
and fear and joy
and sadness

04:39.613 --> 04:41.947
all at once...

04:41.949 --> 04:45.717
all combined
into one magnificent sound.

04:45.719 --> 04:47.452
Where are you from?

04:47.454 --> 04:50.555
Another planet.

04:51.724 --> 04:54.593
What does the bird
sound like?

04:54.595 --> 04:56.528
It sounds like this.

04:56.530 --> 04:58.563
Lean closer.

05:01.802 --> 05:03.502
Geez...

05:03.504 --> 05:05.037
It's more like noise.

05:05.039 --> 05:07.005
Yeah.

05:11.077 --> 05:13.545
And this bird...

05:13.547 --> 05:16.915
when she meets the
love of her life,

05:16.917 --> 05:20.585
is both happy and sad.

05:20.587 --> 05:24.990
Happy because she sees that,
for him, it is the beginning,

05:24.992 --> 05:29.361
and sad because she knows
it is already over.

05:41.408 --> 05:44.076
Hey, hey, do you want
to get a drink?

05:44.078 --> 05:45.744
I don't drink.

05:48.881 --> 05:50.982
Like, anything?

06:36.562 --> 06:39.698
You're not gonna regret this
in the morning, right?

07:41.194 --> 07:42.961
Your identity confirmed.

07:50.736 --> 07:53.705
I finished that
transcription factor program.

07:57.043 --> 07:58.810
Last night?

07:58.812 --> 08:00.645
No.

08:00.647 --> 08:02.147
This morning.

08:02.149 --> 08:05.650
'Cause, bitch, I don't play.

08:05.652 --> 08:07.052
Got the input genes,
and then you put

08:07.054 --> 08:08.220
your transcription factor...
Wait a minute.

08:08.222 --> 08:10.889
You... stink of vodka.

08:10.891 --> 08:12.624
I mean, like, bad.
Like, it smells...

08:12.626 --> 08:14.793
Yeah, I know, I know
I reek off vodka.

08:14.795 --> 08:16.228
Stop talking so loud.

08:16.230 --> 08:18.096
Okay, I consolidated
all your data

08:18.098 --> 08:19.798
into one database.

08:19.800 --> 08:21.199
You are welcome.

08:21.201 --> 08:23.068
You're amazing.
I hate you.

08:23.070 --> 08:25.237
Well, I love you...
that's why I do it.

08:25.239 --> 08:26.505
Oh, hey.

08:26.507 --> 08:29.174
You got a new rotating student.

08:29.176 --> 08:30.642
It's a first-year.

08:30.644 --> 08:32.644
Oh, sh...
Yeah.

08:32.645 --> 08:33.879
Yeah. Yeah.

08:33.881 --> 08:35.947
Have fun
babysitting, buddy.

08:35.948 --> 08:37.515
You need gum.

08:37.518 --> 08:41.119
You need...
to have fun babysitting.

08:41.121 --> 08:44.121
Karen.
Hi. Ian.

08:44.124 --> 08:45.824
Can I...?

08:54.600 --> 08:56.234
Follow me.

08:57.904 --> 09:00.105
<i>You're attempting to make</i>

09:00.107 --> 09:02.674
- color-blind mice see color?
- That's the idea.

09:02.676 --> 09:04.676
But after failed experiment

09:04.678 --> 09:06.945
352...

09:06.947 --> 09:08.146
we'll see.

09:08.148 --> 09:09.314
Why?

09:09.316 --> 09:10.949
Why what?

09:10.951 --> 09:13.285
Do so many experiments fail?

09:13.287 --> 09:17.055
Why are you interested in making
color-blind mice see color?

09:17.057 --> 09:18.757
Oh...

09:18.759 --> 09:20.325
Why not?

09:20.327 --> 09:23.295
How are you testing
that they see color?

09:24.630 --> 09:26.798
As the new rotating
lab assistant,

09:26.800 --> 09:29.968
your job will be
to do very boring,

09:29.970 --> 09:32.037
very repetitive
experiments,

09:32.039 --> 09:34.706
be a glorified note taker,

09:34.708 --> 09:36.841
and not ask me "why"
every five minutes.

09:36.843 --> 09:37.976
Okay?

09:37.978 --> 09:39.177
Cool.

09:39.179 --> 09:41.046
Commencing experiment...

09:41.048 --> 09:43.715
3-5-3,

09:43.717 --> 09:46.651
response to photo pigment
protein in <i> Mus musculus.</i>

09:46.653 --> 09:49.220
The control subjects
B Beta,

09:49.222 --> 09:51.256
G Gamma,

09:51.258 --> 09:53.725
E Euphoria,

09:53.727 --> 09:55.026
P...

09:55.028 --> 09:56.861
Psychopannychia.

09:56.863 --> 09:58.630
I don't know what that means.

09:58.632 --> 09:59.632
Look it up.

09:59.633 --> 10:00.799
"G" as in
goodness gracious,

10:00.801 --> 10:03.301
"H" as in help me, please,

10:03.303 --> 10:05.003
"Z" as in Zoolander,

10:05.005 --> 10:06.938
are the mice muted

10:06.940 --> 10:10.675
with the photo
pigment protein.

10:10.677 --> 10:12.177
When we animate
the lines...

10:12.179 --> 10:14.112
color-blind mice

10:14.114 --> 10:17.315
stare straight.

10:17.317 --> 10:19.317
Whereas...

10:19.319 --> 10:22.253
fingers crossed...

10:22.255 --> 10:24.823
the muted mice... shh...

10:26.859 --> 10:30.028
...track the lines
with their eyes.

10:30.030 --> 10:31.963
Holy shit.
Holy fucking shit.

10:31.965 --> 10:33.832
Is this on the background

10:33.834 --> 10:36.134
of PAX6 overexpression?

10:37.203 --> 10:39.738
You're a first-year?

10:39.740 --> 10:42.707
I know... it's surprising
I can put together a sentence.

10:42.709 --> 10:45.877
Sorry, I... I asked
my last three lab assistants

10:45.879 --> 10:48.313
not to come in
and I'd sign their credits.

10:48.315 --> 10:51.683
Anyway,
this is just one step

10:51.685 --> 10:55.320
in a very, very long... process.

10:55.322 --> 10:58.156
This is a rough estimation,

10:58.158 --> 11:00.191
but let's just say
that the human eye

11:00.193 --> 11:02.260
has 12 working parts, right?

11:02.262 --> 11:04.095
Simplest eye having one.

11:04.097 --> 11:06.231
So if we can
fill in the gaps...

11:06.233 --> 11:07.332
the evolutionary gaps...

11:07.334 --> 11:10.835
using single mutations,

11:10.837 --> 11:14.039
we can map out
the most logical progression

11:14.041 --> 11:16.274
of the most basic eye...

11:16.276 --> 11:20.278
to the most complex,
fully formed human eye.

11:20.280 --> 11:22.914
I don't understand...
why take the time?

11:22.916 --> 11:24.916
We know that it evolved.

11:24.918 --> 11:27.686
It's an assumption;
it's not a fact.

11:27.688 --> 11:31.322
When you're no longer
a first-year, you'll see

11:31.324 --> 11:33.091
how important facts are.

11:33.093 --> 11:34.793
Right.

11:37.296 --> 11:40.331
Each of these animals has an eye

11:40.333 --> 11:43.001
that's best selected
for its environment.

11:44.070 --> 11:46.071
It would be...

11:46.073 --> 11:48.006
cleaner... less variables...

11:48.008 --> 11:50.408
if you... had an origin.

11:51.477 --> 11:53.178
Go on.

11:53.180 --> 11:55.246
You start with one...

11:55.248 --> 11:56.748
to get to 12.

11:56.750 --> 11:59.017
But what if you had zero...

11:59.019 --> 12:01.252
a non-seeing organism...

12:01.254 --> 12:04.322
and built, genetically,
an eye from scratch,

12:04.324 --> 12:06.157
a zero to 12?

12:06.159 --> 12:09.127
It'd be a perfect proof,
unassailable.

12:09.129 --> 12:12.997
Non-seeing organisms
don't have the PAX6 gene.

12:12.999 --> 12:16.167
How do you know? Has anyone
ever checked all of them?

12:16.169 --> 12:19.738
I don't think anyone
has ever checked...

12:19.740 --> 12:21.272
all of them.

12:22.508 --> 12:24.843
You've thought of this before?

12:26.212 --> 12:27.378
Why did you look surprised?

12:27.380 --> 12:29.781
Because so have you.

12:33.352 --> 12:35.453
Okay.

12:41.861 --> 12:43.294
Who were those girls?

12:45.065 --> 12:47.365
Which girls?
The ones at the
Halloween party

12:47.367 --> 12:49.400
in the S&M outfits.

12:49.402 --> 12:51.236
S&M outfits...?

12:51.238 --> 12:53.538
I-I met one of them;
I don't know her name.

12:53.540 --> 12:56.508
I don't know her face, but
she had these most amazing eyes.

12:56.510 --> 12:58.910
So specific.

12:58.912 --> 13:00.178
Central heterochromia.

13:00.180 --> 13:02.514
Oh, reminds me.

13:02.516 --> 13:04.382
Guess what I did.

13:04.384 --> 13:05.850
What?

13:05.852 --> 13:07.919
I... figured out an improved

13:07.921 --> 13:09.220
implementation technique

13:09.222 --> 13:12.357
for Daugman's
biometrics algo.

13:12.359 --> 13:14.459
You ever feel like
when you met someone,

13:14.461 --> 13:16.060
they fill this hole
inside of you,

13:16.062 --> 13:17.362
and then when they're gone...

13:17.364 --> 13:21.299
you feel that space
painfully vacant?

13:22.334 --> 13:24.269
Are you okay, man?

13:26.372 --> 13:28.173
Yeah, yeah, I'm okay.

13:28.175 --> 13:29.407
Are you okay?

13:29.409 --> 13:31.576
What did you just say?
Did you just...

13:31.578 --> 13:33.578
The way you talked was,
like, poetic.

13:33.580 --> 13:35.880
It was weird.
Shut the fuck up.

13:35.882 --> 13:38.016
So weird, dude,
I can't believe...

13:38.018 --> 13:39.851
Oh, shit.

13:41.420 --> 13:44.389
This guy is painfully vacant.

13:44.391 --> 13:46.391
Ian, look at him...
he's so painfully va...

13:46.393 --> 13:49.994
He's so painfully vacant.

13:49.996 --> 13:52.197
Fuck off.

13:58.904 --> 14:01.072
Can I get a-a pack of Verdict

14:01.074 --> 14:03.241
and a Powerball?

14:05.277 --> 14:08.112
How much is that?

14:10.317 --> 14:11.983
$11.11.

14:11.985 --> 14:13.184
Eleven...

14:20.026 --> 14:22.360
Lucky elevens.

14:25.998 --> 14:28.299
Thanks.

17:09.661 --> 17:12.195
Karen.
Mm-hmm?

17:12.198 --> 17:14.198
What are you doing?

17:14.200 --> 17:16.666
Five percent of all animals
don't have vision,

17:16.669 --> 17:19.037
and there are
8.7 million species.

17:19.039 --> 17:21.772
So I blasted PAX6
at the database,

17:21.775 --> 17:23.508
but nothing came up.

17:23.510 --> 17:25.143
So I started sequencing
by myself.

17:25.145 --> 17:27.244
How many did you sequence?

17:28.414 --> 17:31.816
12.
You've done 12.

17:31.818 --> 17:35.219
So how many do
you have left?

17:35.221 --> 17:39.323
Like, approximately
426,000.

17:39.325 --> 17:43.628
Are you going to write
426,000 names

17:43.630 --> 17:45.396
on the window?

17:47.232 --> 17:50.835
I'm going to find it before
I get to the end of the window.

17:50.837 --> 17:52.203
Okay.

17:52.205 --> 17:54.172
What are you doing?

17:55.441 --> 17:57.542
I'm... I'm not doing anything.

18:46.825 --> 18:50.695
You know we could be looking
forever and find nothing.

18:50.697 --> 18:55.399
Turning over rocks
and finding nothing is progress.

21:32.958 --> 21:35.059
<i>So, are you gonna tell me
where you're from?</i>

21:37.329 --> 21:38.996
So many places, I don't know.

21:38.998 --> 21:42.500
Which places?

21:42.502 --> 21:44.802
Mm...

21:44.804 --> 21:48.673
To make it short,
I was born in Argentina,

21:48.675 --> 21:52.510
and when I was 11, I moved
to France with my grandmother.

21:56.882 --> 21:59.383
And your-your parents?

22:00.452 --> 22:02.420
Next.

22:06.692 --> 22:09.026
So, what do you do?

22:09.028 --> 22:10.461
Next.

22:17.035 --> 22:19.337
Why did you sleep
with me that night?

22:20.405 --> 22:22.873
Poor judgment.

22:25.610 --> 22:28.713
I was lonely
for a long time, and...

22:31.950 --> 22:33.684
...when I saw you that night,

22:33.686 --> 22:37.555
I... I had the feeling
that I had known you.

22:37.557 --> 22:40.958
Actually, I felt like
you knew me.

22:40.960 --> 22:44.428
What do you mean?

22:45.697 --> 22:48.599
Like we are connected
from past lives.

22:49.634 --> 22:52.069
I don't believe in that.

22:54.139 --> 22:56.774
What do you believe in?

22:56.776 --> 22:59.443
I'm a scientist;
I believe in data.

22:59.445 --> 23:00.878
A scientist?
Mm-hmm.

23:00.880 --> 23:02.480
What kind of scientist?

23:02.482 --> 23:03.781
Molecular biology.

23:03.783 --> 23:06.517
I'm most fascinated
with the eye.

23:06.519 --> 23:07.985
The eye... the-the eyes?

23:07.987 --> 23:09.120
The eyes.
Why the eye?

23:09.122 --> 23:10.788
The eye is

23:10.790 --> 23:12.790
the one sticking point
that religious people use

23:12.792 --> 23:15.059
to discredit evolution.

23:15.061 --> 23:18.129
They use it as proof of a...
intelligent designer.

23:18.131 --> 23:19.964
Intelligent designer...?

23:19.966 --> 23:21.732
God.

23:21.734 --> 23:25.436
I'm looking to end the debate
once and for all with...

23:27.773 --> 23:30.474
...clear, clean facts.

23:30.476 --> 23:32.610
Data points of every stage
of eye evolution.

23:32.612 --> 23:36.614
Why are you working so hard
to disprove God?

23:36.616 --> 23:39.784
Disprove? Who proved that God
was there in the first place?

23:41.787 --> 23:45.489
Anyway,
let's get some real

23:45.491 --> 23:47.124
data points on you, okay?

23:47.126 --> 23:48.559
Be my guest.

23:48.561 --> 23:51.195
I prefer talking
about myself anyways.

23:51.197 --> 23:53.097
Okay.

23:53.099 --> 23:55.966
<i>Um, what's your favorite,
um...</i>

23:55.968 --> 23:58.436
<i>Candy?</i>

23:58.438 --> 23:59.637
<i>Strawberry Mentos.</i>

23:59.639 --> 24:01.739
<i>Food?</i>

24:01.741 --> 24:03.707
<i>Veggie burritos.</i>

24:03.709 --> 24:05.075
<i>I'm vegetarian,
you should know that.</i>

24:05.077 --> 24:09.046
<i>What's your favorite flower?</i>

24:09.048 --> 24:11.115
<i>Dandelions.</i>

24:11.117 --> 24:13.050
<i>Okay. Why?</i>

24:13.052 --> 24:16.220
<i>'Cause, they're free, wild,</i>

24:16.222 --> 24:18.656
<i>and you can't buy them.</i>

24:18.658 --> 24:21.192
<i>What's your favorite
field of study?</i>

24:21.194 --> 24:22.760
<i>The stars.</i>

24:22.762 --> 24:24.628
<i>What's your favorite animal?</i>

24:24.630 --> 24:25.996
<i>The white peacock.</i>

24:25.998 --> 24:27.965
<i>You ever see one?</i>

24:27.967 --> 24:29.467
<i>No.</i>

24:29.469 --> 24:30.801
<i>There's one in New York.</i>

24:30.803 --> 24:33.237
<i>I'll take you to see it.</i>

24:33.239 --> 24:36.540
<i>So, you're gonna see me again?</i>

24:36.542 --> 24:38.008
<i>Maybe.</i>

24:47.652 --> 24:51.789
<i>You know,
in Indian mythology,</i>

24:51.791 --> 24:53.724
<i>the white peacock symbolizes</i>

24:53.726 --> 24:56.760
<i>souls being dispersed
throughout the world.</i>

24:56.762 --> 24:59.196
<i>Did you ever think
it just symbolizes</i>

24:59.198 --> 25:02.132
<i>a lack of melanin or pigment
in the cells?</i>

25:04.769 --> 25:06.704
<i>The control subjects "T..."</i>

25:06.706 --> 25:09.106
<i>"T" as in tsunami.</i>

25:09.108 --> 25:10.574
<i>"G" as in...</i>

25:10.576 --> 25:11.576
<i>Gnome.</i>

25:11.577 --> 25:13.077
<i>"P" as in...</i>

25:13.079 --> 25:14.912
<i>Pneumonia.</i>

25:14.914 --> 25:16.080
<i>"M" as in...</i>

25:16.082 --> 25:17.281
<i>Mnemonic.</i>

25:42.240 --> 25:45.209
I start to see these elevens,
like, everywhere.

25:45.211 --> 25:46.911
Too many elevens.

25:46.913 --> 25:50.281
The amount was
so staggering, so unlikely,

25:50.283 --> 25:53.150
that I followed them.

25:53.152 --> 25:55.619
And when I followed them,
I found your eyes,

25:55.621 --> 25:58.055
which then led me to you.

25:58.057 --> 26:00.291
Because I found you
through your eyes.

26:00.293 --> 26:03.060
Also unlikely...

26:03.062 --> 26:05.162
like life itself.

26:05.164 --> 26:08.799
I know.

26:08.801 --> 26:10.801
I sent them to you.

26:10.803 --> 26:12.770
Bullshit.

26:16.641 --> 26:18.842
You know you have it.

26:18.844 --> 26:21.084
Have what?
But you're scared of it.

26:23.281 --> 26:25.249
I have what?

26:32.591 --> 26:34.358
Okay.

26:39.030 --> 26:41.031
You live in this room, right?

26:41.033 --> 26:42.199
Mm-hmm.

26:42.201 --> 26:44.134
Reality.

26:44.136 --> 26:47.805
You have a bed, you have books,

26:47.807 --> 26:51.675
um, a desk, a chair, lamps.

26:51.677 --> 26:54.144
Logic.

26:54.146 --> 26:55.980
But in this room,

26:55.982 --> 26:58.716
you have a door...

26:58.718 --> 27:00.050
to the other side.

27:02.087 --> 27:03.988
See?

27:03.990 --> 27:07.358
Light comes through.

27:07.360 --> 27:09.259
It's open

27:09.261 --> 27:14.231
just a tiny bit,
but it is open.

27:14.233 --> 27:18.202
You keep trying to close
that door because you're scared.

27:20.105 --> 27:23.140
But you won't always
be scared.

27:26.144 --> 27:28.345
What's behind the door?

27:28.347 --> 27:30.214
Besides my dirty laundry.

27:30.216 --> 27:32.776
You have to go
in to find out.

27:33.385 --> 27:35.953
You know
what I'm talking about.

27:39.824 --> 27:42.292
I have no idea.

27:42.294 --> 27:44.795
You will.

27:44.797 --> 27:46.764
You will.

27:48.133 --> 27:49.867
Oh...

27:49.869 --> 27:52.136
You want to move to my place?

27:52.138 --> 27:53.671
You have a place?

27:53.673 --> 27:56.006
Mm-hmm. Of course.

